Mr Ahmed and his company claim that the NLC left them out of a hearing that was to determine the property’s owner and awarded it to Mr Nzuki, who was partially represented in the hearings by Ms Ndeti.
While court papers state that Mr Nzuki and the Transport CAS are related, they do not specify how.
Ms Ndeti’s late father was also called Mr Peter Nzuki Ndeti but the Nation was yet to establish whether he is the same individual in the Athi River land saga. The land is currently valued at over Sh400 million. Part of the land is set to be acquired by the government to pave way for the dualling of the Athi River-Machakos highway.





Two years ago, Mr Ahmed sued at the High Court claiming that he bought the land in 2004 and had subdivided it into 18 plots, one of which has been leased to petroleum dealer Engen.
Tinek Limited
The NLC in its defence said that its decision was based on a claim by Mr Nzuki that he has occupied the land since 1960 alongside a woman identified as Elizabeth Nzili Ndeti.
On May 8, 2020, Justice Oscar Angote quashed the NLC’s decision to award Mr Nzuki the property, but also revoked the title deed held by Tinek Limited.
Justice Angote’s decision has left the ownership of the land in limbo, as both parties claiming ownership have lost their respective bids.



