Mr Ahmed and Tinek Limited have, however, challenged Justice Angote’s ruling at Court of Appeal.
Apart from being declared the legal owner, Tinek and Mr Ahmed are looking to have the NLC compelled to pay them Sh197 million as compensation for part of the land that is set to be acquired for dualling of the Athi River-Machakos highway.
Trouble started in 2016 when Mr Nzuki filed a complaint with the NLC, claiming that his land had been irregularly acquired by Mr Ahmed and Tinek Limited.
At the time, the Kenya National Highways Authority (KeNHA) was on the verge of paying Tinek Limited Sh197 million as compensation for the parcels that would be acquired compulsorily acquired.
Dispute
The NLC was to hear the dispute on January 27, 2016 but the proceedings were adjourned to November 4 same year.
On the new hearing date, Mr Ahmed filed an objection stating that Tinek Limited was an innocent purchaser for value and that since 2004, it had never received a complaint about ownership.
Mr Ahmed said he acquired the land by buying all the shares in Tinek Limited. On July 16, 2017, when the matter was to proceed, Mr Nzuki said he was bereaved.
Mr Ahmed and his lawyers went to NLC offices on the same day and met with then vice chairperson Abigael Mbagaya.



