The gazette notice stated that the NLC had made a ruling on April 27, 2017— three months before the first hearing was conducted.
NLC insisted in court that it held a hearing on January 26, 2016 and that Tinek Limited and Mr Ahmed provided their evidence and version of events.
Provide evidence
The agency added that its decision followed Tinek Limited’s failure to provide evidence of initial allocation.
In the High Court, Tinek filed a letter of allotment issued to a woman identified as Lucy Njeri Mwangi in 1990 in respect of the same land.
But the title deed issued to Tinek Limited indicated that the land was first registered to the firm.
Justice Angote ruled that the inconsistency was an indication that Tinek Limited’s title deed is irregular.  The Court of Appeal has now suspended the execution of Justice Angote’s judgment until it has determined the challenge.



